   (Message) The crash is caused by the bad variant intentionally overflowing a
   stack buffer inside a struct.
   
   In `program.c`, the relevant type is:
   
   ```c
   typedef struct _charVoid
   {
       char charFirst[16];
       void * voidSecond;
       void * voidThird;
   } charVoid;
   ```
   
   In the bad function:
   
   ```c
   void CWE121_Stack_Based_Buffer_Overflow__char_type_overrun_memcpy_01_bad()
   {
       {
           charVoid structCharVoid;
           structCharVoid.voidSecond = (void *)SRC_STR;
           printLine((char *)structCharVoid.voidSecond);
   
           /* FLAW */
           memcpy(structCharVoid.charFirst, SRC_STR, sizeof(structCharVoid));
   
           structCharVoid.charFirst[(sizeof(structCharVoid.charFirst)/sizeof(char))-1] = '\0';
           printLine((char *)structCharVoid.charFirst);
           printLine((char *)structCharVoid.voidSecond);
       }
   }
   ```
   
   `structCharVoid.charFirst` is only 16 bytes, but the code copies
   `sizeof(structCharVoid)` bytes into it. In the debugger,
   `sizeof(structCharVoid)` is 32 while `sizeof(structCharVoid.charFirst)` is
   16. So this call:
   
   ```c
   memcpy(structCharVoid.charFirst, SRC_STR, sizeof(structCharVoid));
   ```
   
   copies 32 bytes into a 16-byte array.
   
   Because `charFirst` is the first field in the struct, the extra 16 bytes
   overwrite the following fields:
   
   ```text
   offset 0..15   -> charFirst[16]
   offset 16..23  -> voidSecond
   offset 24..31  -> voidThird
   ```
   
   `SRC_STR` is:
   
   ```c
   "0123456789abcdef0123456789abcde"
   ```
   
   So after the overflowing copy, the bytes that land in `voidSecond` are ASCII
   characters from the source string. The debugger shows:
   
   ```text
   structCharVoid.voidSecond = 0x3736353433323130
   ```
   
   That value is not the original pointer to `SRC_STR`; it is the little-endian
   interpretation of the bytes:
   
   ```text
   '0' '1' '2' '3' '4' '5' '6' '7'
   ```
   
   as a pointer value.
   
   Then line 45 does:
   
   ```c
   printLine((char *)structCharVoid.voidSecond);
   ```
   
   which passes `0x3736353433323130` to `printf("%s\n", line)`.
   `printf`/`strlen` tries to read a C string from that bogus address and
   segfaults:
   
   ```text
   line = 0x3736353433323130 <error: Cannot access memory at address ...>
   SIGSEGV
   ```
   
   So the crash is not caused by `printLine` itself. `printLine` is only where
   the corrupted pointer is dereferenced. The actual memory corruption happens
   earlier at `program.c:42`.
   
   A minimal fix is to copy only the size of the destination array, not the size
   of the whole struct:
   
   ```diff
   -        memcpy(structCharVoid.charFirst, SRC_STR, sizeof(structCharVoid));
   +        memcpy(structCharVoid.charFirst, SRC_STR, sizeof(structCharVoid.charFirst));
   ```
   
   That is exactly what the good variant does.
   
   A safer version would also make the intended string-copying semantics
   explicit:
   
   ```c
   memcpy(structCharVoid.charFirst, SRC_STR, sizeof(structCharVoid.charFirst) - 1);
   structCharVoid.charFirst[sizeof(structCharVoid.charFirst) - 1] = '\0';
   ```
   
   or:
   
   ```c
   snprintf(structCharVoid.charFirst,
            sizeof(structCharVoid.charFirst),
            "%s",
            SRC_STR);
   ```
   
   The latter avoids manually managing the terminator.
   
   ROOT CAUSE: `program.c:42` copies `sizeof(structCharVoid)` bytes into
   `structCharVoid.charFirst`, whose actual capacity is only
   `sizeof(structCharVoid.charFirst)`. This overwrites adjacent struct fields,
   including `voidSecond`. `voidSecond` becomes the bogus pointer value
   `0x3736353433323130`, derived from copied ASCII bytes, and the later
   `printLine((char *)structCharVoid.voidSecond)` dereferences that invalid
   pointer, causing `SIGSEGV`.
   
   LOCAL FIX:
   
   ```diff
   diff --git a/program.c b/program.c
   --- a/program.c
   +++ b/program.c
   @@ -39,7 +39,7 @@ void CWE121_Stack_Based_Buffer_Overflow__char_type_overrun_memcpy_01_bad()
            /* Print the initial block pointed to by structCharVoid.voidSecond */
            printLine((char *)structCharVoid.voidSecond);
   -        /* FLAW: Use the sizeof(structCharVoid) which will overwrite the pointer voidSecond */
   -        memcpy(structCharVoid.charFirst, SRC_STR, sizeof(structCharVoid));
   +        /* Copy only into the charFirst buffer */
   +        memcpy(structCharVoid.charFirst, SRC_STR, sizeof(structCharVoid.charFirst));
            structCharVoid.charFirst[(sizeof(structCharVoid.charFirst)/sizeof(char))-1] = '\0';
            printLine((char *)structCharVoid.charFirst);
            printLine((char *)structCharVoid.voidSecond);
   ```
   
   GLOBAL FIX: Avoid raw size-based copying into embedded arrays where the
   destination object and destination field have different sizes. Encapsulate
   fixed-size string fields behind a bounded API, for example a helper that
   takes the destination array size explicitly or use `snprintf`/`strlcpy`-style
   bounded string functions. More structurally, replace raw `char[N]` plus
   manual `memcpy` with a dedicated bounded string abstraction or macro that
   derives the destination array size from the actual field and prevents passing
   the enclosing struct size by mistake.
